<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAR 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: UK threatens France over fish
deliveries disruption
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK threatened last night to take France to the European Court in protest
over violent disruption of deliveries of British fish mounted by French
fishermen.
Mr Allan Stewart, a junior Scottish Office minister, said Britain might
'need to have recourse to the European institutions' if 'quick redress' for
the incidents was not forthcoming.
He said he was encouraged by France's response to requests to provide
protection for British cargoes when notice was given.
British officials had made it clear to their French counterparts that they
were monitoring fresh incidents perpetrated by French fishermen some of whom
were 'totally out of control,' he said.
He urged the French authorities to 'act to restore order.'
Clashes between police and fishermen protesting against the increase in
imports of cheap fish into France reached a climax some ten days ago when
800 fishermen stormed the vast wholesale fish market at Rungis on the
outskirts of Paris, leaving hundreds of tonnes of damaged fish strewn over
the floor.
Only a few hours later Mr John Major, the prime minister, promised at
Westminster that he would leave France 'in no doubt' that those who had
earlier attacked a British consignment of fish in Brittany should be brought
to book.
France would be told it was expected to act where necessary to 'safeguard
free trade, to pay compensation when losses have occurred and to bring the
perpetrators to book.'
Mr Major's response followed demands by Tory MPs yesterday that the prime
minister raise the issue with the French government and ensure compensation
was paid to 'all in Britain who have lost cash.'
That spate of violence was calmed by French government assurances that the
EC would agree to impose minimum prices on imported fish.
Yesterday's threat came in a Commons debate called by Mr Phil Gallie, the
Tory MP for Ayr, to discuss fish exports through France, and particularly
the question of damage and compensation to a local Scottish company.
Claiming that Pounds 10,000 worth of 'Clyde-caught fish' was destroyed in a
French market by having diesel poured over it, Mr Gallie said that the
recent violence had caused 'a serious disruption totrade.'
A total of Pounds 2.5m worth of damage had been done and five French
fishermen had been arrested, he added.
Mr David Harris, Conservative MP for St Ives, said British exporters were
now afraid to use British transport for fear their produce would be
immediately set on by 'thugs.'
</TEXT>
