<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAR 93 / World Commodities Prices: Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PLATINUM was fixed at Dollars 340.75 a troy ounce in the afternoon on the
London bullion market - still Dollars 2 down from the Wednesday's close but
Dollars 1 above the morning, its lowest fix since January 22, 1992.
'Platinum is falling although I'm not sure that it wants to. If there is
going to be a big move, I think it will be down rather than up,' said one
analyst. GOLD traded in a tight range, limited on the downside by good
physical demand at Dollars 327 to Dollars 328 a troy ounce. Sentiment
remains bearish on the LME following the losses of the last week, and
although most markets consolidated in narrow ranges yesterday, rallies were
seen as fresh selling opportunities. Three-month COPPER spent most of the
day above Dollars 2,150 a tonne, but was unable to push significantly
higher, and prices eased back under late liquidation. Final business was at
Dollars 2,145. Three-month ALUMINIUM continued to encounter resistance on
moves towards Dollars 1,190, and gradually lost heart, settling back to end
at Dollars 1,182.25.
Compiled from Reuters
</TEXT>
