<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAR 93 / International Company News: Profits slip by 22% at The Gap
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GAP, the San Francisco-based specialty retailer which until recently was
one of Wall Street's darling stocks, yesterday reported a 22 per cent
decline in fourth-quarter profits.
The company, which operates over 1,300 stores under The Gap, Banana Republic
and GapKids names, said after-tax profits in the 13 weeks to January 30,
fell from Dollars 83.8m to Dollars 65.7m. Sales increased from Dollars
803.5m to Dollars 930.2m.
The final quarter's figures leave The Gap's profits for the year at Dollars
210.7m after tax, down from Dollars 229.9m in the previous 12 months. Sales
totalled Dollars 2.96bn, compared with Dollars 2.52bn.
Mr Donald Fisher, The Gap's chairman, blamed the downturn, which was
concentrated in the core domestic Gap division, on 'the effect on
merchandise margins of lower retail prices and higher occupancy expenses'.
He noted that GapKids and Banana Republic outlets, with the company's
overseas stores, all posted higher profits.
Part of The Gap's problems stem from intense competition in the domestic
market from rival retailers of basic items like jeans, T-shirts and
sweaters. As a result, the San Francisco company cut its denim prices last
year, affecting its gross margins.
</TEXT>
