<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAR 93 / International Company News: Salomon hit by Dollars 250m loss
for first two months
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES in Salomon, the Wall Street securities house and energy trading
group, fell yesterday after the company revealed it had incurred a pre-tax
operating loss of about Dollars 250m for the first two months of this year.
Salomon attributed the loss to its proprietary trading activities, where the
company takes long-term bets on a wide range of mostly fixed-income
securities. Because those trading positions are directly affected by
movements in interest rates, they can be highly volatile over short periods.
The actual loss from proprietary trading may have been larger than Dollars
250m, because the figure announced yesterday reflects the pre-tax income
from all of Salomon's businesses. They include investment banking, which is
likely to have been very profitable recently because of heavy demand for
underwriting services from US and foreign companies, and the trading and
refining of oil and related products.
Analysts believe the loss is related to Salomon's big arbitrage portfolio,
which employs several billion dollars of the firm's assets to invest in
fixed-income, mostly government, securities.
Although the value of the portfolio can change rapidly from one week to the
next, Salomon does not sell those positions when they shift. However, the
firm has to regularly calculate their value at current market prices for
accounting purposes.
Analysts warned not to make too much of the announcement. Mr John Keefe, an
independent analyst with Keefe Worldwide Services, said: 'For the short term
it looks as if they were in the wrong place at the wrong time. But for the
long term, Salomon remains an expert trader and their proprietary activities
should do well for them.'
Salomon would not reveal what caused the loss, but there was speculation on
Wall Street that the company's traders may have bet that the recent rally in
US bond prices was about to end. As one analyst said: 'Solly could have been
leaning into the wind and expecting the bond market to reverse itself.' In
fact, US bond prices have soared to record levels in recent weeks.
Yesterday's announcement was unusual because US companies normally reveal
earnings details only every three months. However, Salomon is a regular
issuer of debt, and the company is likely to have felt the size of the loss,
even if it may be temporary, had to be divulged to potential buyers of its
securities.
This has happened to Salomon before. In the third quarter of last year the
company reported weak earnings following a big drop in proprietary trading
profits. On Wall Street, Salomon shares fell Dollars 1 7/8 to Dollars 39
5/8.
</TEXT>
