FT  05 MAR 93 / UK Company News: Overseas fall behind 27% dip at Renishaw
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RENISHAW, the maker of precision measuring probes and inspection equipment,
reported a 27 per cent fall in interim profits as its main industrial
markets suffered, particularly Japan, France and Germany.
Sales of co-ordinate measuring machines and laser calibration products
increased but demand for measuring probes fell in line with recession in the
machine tool sector.
Pre-tax profits in the six months to December fell from Pounds 4.18m to
Pounds 3.07m on sales up 3.3 per cent at Pounds 22m.
Earnings per share fell from 6.1p to 4.4p but the interim dividend is
maintained at 2.5p.
Mr David McMurtry, chairman and chief executive, said the group had
increased marketing in emerging Far East markets while a new subsidiary had
been set up in Hong Kong.
The North American market was showing signs of recovery and there were
indications that other markets had also reached a floor.
'This leads us to believe that the demand for our products, might now begin
to recover,' Mr McMurtry said.
</TEXT>
