FT  05 MAR 93 / UK Company News: Skipton hit by loans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRE-TAX PROFITS of the Skipton Building Society fell 50 per cent to Pounds
4.1m in 1992 as the society increased its bad debt provision to Pounds
42.2m, writes Philip Coggan.
The society was also forced to restate its 1991 accounts to address a
'fundamental error'. Having taken the advice of its auditors and other
advisers, a further provision of Pounds 3.25m was taken in respect of one
commercial loan.
This reduced the 1991 pre-tax profits, previously stated as Pounds 11.5m, to
Pounds 8.2m, and increased that year's bad debt provision to Pounds 27.5m.
Over half the society's provision for bad debts in 1992 relate to commercial
loans. Mr John Goodfellow, chief executive, said that the society had been
exposed to the leisure sector and that pubs and hotels had been badly hit by
recession.
Operating profits rose 30 per cent to Pounds 46.3m (Pounds 35.7m) in 1992
helped by an increase in interest margins and a reduction in management
expenses. The cost to income ratio fell from 39.8 per cent to 32.7 per cent.
</TEXT>
