<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAR 93 / UK Company News: Hambro Countrywide cuts loss to Pounds 3m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HAMBRO Countrywide, the estate agency and financial services chain, cut its
pre-tax loss from Pounds 6.49m to Pounds 3.14m in the 12 months to December
31.
However, the result, prepared on the basis of FRS 3, included a gain of
Pounds 6.06m from the sale of a 49 per cent holding in Hambro Legal
Protection.
Turnover fell from Pounds 93.2m to Pounds 90.8m, with losses per share up
from 0.95p to 0.99p. As in 1992, the company is proposing to pass the final
dividend, leaving shareholders with the nominal 0.05p per share paid after
the interim results.
Pointing to estimates that the number of houses sold nationally fell by 23
per cent during 1992, the company believed it did well to achieve sales down
by only 3.2 per cent.
The loss on the estate agency side was Pounds 13.6m, offset by profits from
the sale of financial products. Hambro Guardian Consultancy arranged 6,918
policies, up 95 per cent.
The estate agency chain was cut from 487 branches to 455. Mr John May,
managing director, said that with a significant revival of business there
were no plans for further cuts. The company was instead looking for
'expansion in due course'.
Net debt rose to Pounds 12.3m (Pounds 11.9m) at the year end, taking gearing
to 23 per cent (22 per cent).
To break even on estate agency this year, the company estimated it needs to
increase sales from last year's 39,000 to about 43,000. On the basis of
sales in the first two months - February was the best month since June 1988
 -it believes it is well ahead of that target. But, added Mr May, 'recovery
is fragile and many challenges and uncertainties remain'.
UBS Phillips and Drew are forecasting a return to the black for the first
time since 1988, with profits of about Pounds 5m for the group this year.
