<PROFILE>_AN-DCEB6AEBFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930305
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAR 93 / Damage of property slump will continue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PROPERTY lending was the most conspicuous, if not the most important, cause
of Barclays' problems last year.
Barclays was a principal banker to companies such as Rosehaugh, Mountleigh,
Speyhawk, Heron, Olympia &amp; York and Imry. The write-down on Imry alone was
Pounds 240m, one of the largest provisions in banking history.
The pain is not yet over. Barclays, which yesterday provided against 10 per
cent of its Pounds 7.7bn UK property and construction loan book, expects to
take more, if smaller, provisions next year.
Barclays, the largest lender to UK property, may be worse-placed than its
peers, but it is not alone. The banks which together lent some Pounds 40bn
to UK property are expected to write off billions of pounds between them.
Estimates of banks' total provisions against property loans range widely.
More sanguine commentators point out that at least half of the banks'
property debt was agreed before 1988.
But the banks have a disproportionately high exposure to unlet buildings and
development sites, which are worth a small fraction of their value a few
years ago. This suggests the assets that make up the banks' security may
have fallen by far more than 40 per cent, the average fall in commercial
property values since May 1989.
Banks have considerable discretion in the extent of provisioning, which
largely depends on their view of a company's prospects. Many advisers
believe banks are not fully provisioning, partly because they want to spread
the damage over time and partly because they have insufficient resources to
devote to sorting out their bad property loans. 'A lot of banks are sitting
on problems. They are not even looking at them' says Mr Richard Millward of
Kleinwort Benson's workout unit.
But provisions against property loans may be the tip of the iceberg for
banks. A bigger problem is the the effect on their collateral, since
property is the security against the huge majority of banks loans. The
damage inflicted by the collapse in property values is far deeper than the
provisions against property loans may suggest.
</TEXT>
<XX>
