<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAR 93 / Maastricht amendment rejected: Government relief as move to
wreck ratification is thrown out
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT breathed a collective sigh of relief last night when an
amendment that threatened to wreck ratification of the Maastricht treaty was
ruled out of order.
The decision by Mr Michael Morris, the deputy speaker, represents a serious
setback for the Conservative Euro-sceptic faction, who saw the amendment as
their best chance of sinking the treaty.
But it does not halt debate in the near future of another Labour change to
the bill that, if passed, could force the government to choose between
accepting the social chapter or abandoning the treaty.
The amendment thrown out yesterday, tabled by Labour's Mr Calum Macdonald,
aimed to remove the entire social protocol from the treaty, including
Britain's 'opt-out', thereby implicitly forcing a full renegotiation of the
pact.
Mr Morris has yet to rule on the Labour leadership's amendment, tabled on
Wednesday, which could be heard later this month.
Nonetheless, yesterday's ruling has taken the pressure off the government
after days of it looking extremely vulnerable to a defeat that would have
had disastrous ramifications for its European policy.
Additional respite came when a widely anticipated row in the Tory backbench
1922 committee over Maastricht policy failed to materialise.
In spite of these developments, ministers remain highly sensitive to opinion
among rightwing Euro-sceptic rebels.
Mr George Robertson, Labour spokesman on European affairs, said there was a
Tory 'chasm' over Maastricht: 'The Conservative party is a shambles, a
rabble out of control, without the slightest atom of knowledge of where they
are going to go on Europe, or, indeed, anywhere else.'
He charged that the government failed at Maastricht to ensure that bodies
such as the European parliament had enough powers to counter the strength of
'crude market forces and faceless bureaucrats and bankers'.
Mr Robertson faced down complaints from Tory Euro-sceptics that the basic
unity between the front benches over Maastricht made the Commons debate 'a
sham'.
Elsewhere ministers are going on the offensive against their backbench
critics on Europe.
In a speech to businessmen in Westminster yesterday Mr William Waldegrave,
the public services minister, condemned opponents of the treaty as
'flat-earthers' and told Conservative backbenchers to stop squabbling like
children.
'Of course Maastricht is a compromise - every deal one does with one's
partners always is - but it is the best on offer and much better than its
predecessor, the Single European Act,' the minister said.
He was later taken to task over his comments on BBC television by Tory
Euro-rebel Sir Teddy Taylor, who told him: 'Abuse doesn't solve anything,'
adding that the opponents of the Maastricht treaty are 'reluctant rebels. We
want to work together with the party'.
Mr Waldegrave's strong comments came on the eve of two further attacks on
the governments' backbench critics, expected to be similarly robust.
Mr Douglas Hurd and Mr Kenneth Clarke are both due to use the Conservative
Central Council meeting in Harrogate today to launch new assaults on the
party's dissidents.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
