<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAR 93 / Wandsworth to get more than 8% of council tax relief funds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Conservative-controlled London borough of Wandsworth is to get Pounds
28m of the Pounds 340m national budget for transitional relief to ease the
introduction of the council tax.
Wandsworth, with 0.5 per cent of the population of England, is to receive
more than 8 per cent of the money, it emerged yesterday. The borough, which
announced its council tax levels for 1993-94, will qualify for more than
Pounds 28m of the Pounds 340m budget provided for transitional relief by the
Department of the Environment.
Its residents will pay what is likely to be one of the lowest council tax
rates in the country, at an average of Pounds 145 for a band D house - worth
between Pounds 68,000 and Pounds 88,000.
The average Band D council tax bill for England is likely to be around
Pounds 550, according to a survey carried out by Public Finance and
Accountancy magazine and Channel 4 News. The survey is based on tax figures
adopted or recommended by 410 of the 419 local authorities in England.
A further Pounds 9.5m of transitional relief will go to Westminster, another
Conservative-controlled London borough, to hold the Band D tax down to
Pounds 202. The boroughs - regarded as Tory flagship councils - will
together account for more than 11 per cent of the transitional relief total.
The Environment Department confirmed yesterday that Wandsworth would have
swallowed a bigger share of transitional relief if the rules had not been
hurriedly changed to stop the borough setting a budget to maximise the
relief it received.
The rules for transitional relief, announced last November by Mr Michael
Howard, the environment secretary, were meant to limit to Pounds 130 a year
the maximum increase band D households will have to pay over their last poll
tax bill.
However, it became apparent that Wandsworth planned to increase its budget
by much more than was necessary to maintain services at last year's levels,
using transitional relief to hold down household bills. Since Wandsworth had
levied a zero poll tax for the past two years, the maximum council tax
payable in a Band D home would be Pounds 130 - with transitional relief
paying any extra.
The cost of the transitional relief for Wandsworth would have been Pounds
35m, pushing the total bill for the relief over its cash limit. To avoid
this, the transitional relief paid to Wandsworth was capped by changes to
the rules notified to local authority chief executives on Monday.
Though the change will in theory apply to every council, officials do not
expect more than one or two to be affected in practice.
Mr Jack Straw, Labour's environment spokesman, accused Wandsworth council of
trying to use taxpayers' money to improve services to boost the
Conservatives' chances of survival in the London borough elections next
year.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>GOVT  Government News.
    GOVT  Taxes.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
