<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Discharging the honourables - A
lack of enthusiasm about the planned reforms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GRIN AND bear it was the order of the day yesterday in officers' messes as
Mr John Major announced his reform of the honours system.
It was not a revolt over the effect of the changes on military decorations,
but there was a distinct lack of enthusiasm among senior ranks of the armed
forces about the way Mr Major's vision of a classless and meritocratic
society was being applied.
'Are we actually achieving any great improvement?' mused one brigadier. But
he added: 'I don't think anyone would die in a ditch over the changes.' The
armed services have no wish to be depicted as diehard opponents of change.
But by their nature they are hierarchical, and few felt strongly that the
principle of different awards for different ranks was misplaced or wrong.
'There was never a great discussion about it,' another long-serving officer
said.
The hardest change to swallow is the loss of automatic knighthoods for those
reaching 'three-star' level - lieutenant general, vice-admiral or air
marshal.
'They don't get much else, poor things,' said a retired major general, whose
army career ended one rank short of automatic knighthood.
A former senior army commander commented: 'If he were an American you would
give him a huge increase in salary, a thick carpet on the floor and a couple
of extra secretaries.'
So few make it to the top of their services nowadays that they deserved
their knighthoods, he said. The number of officers on the active list in
three-star posts and above - now about 50 - is due to shrink by a quarter or
more in the cuts in the armed forces.
Abolition of the two-tier system of gallantry awards, dating from the first
world war, was widely seen as inevitable. Until now only officers could win
the Distinguished Service Order. The equivalent for other ranks has been the
Distinguished Conduct Medal in the army or Conspicuous Gallantry Medal in
the navy or RAF.
One step lower, the Military Cross, Distinguished Service Cross or
Distinguished Flying Cross were for officers, while others had 'medals'
instead of 'crosses' pinned on them. The only decoration available to all
ranks, dating back to the Crimean war, was the top bravery award, the
Victoria Cross.
The Most Excellent Order of the British Empire, with its separate military
division, was also a first world war invention. Ranks below warrant officer,
excluded from any of the classes of the order, earned British Empire Medals
instead, for 'meritorious service'. They will now share the MBE awards with
majors and squadron leaders - but not with higher ranks, who rate OBEs or
CBEs.
If the military is slightly aggrieved by the reform it is because it sets
store by its special relationship with the Crown. After all, even the titles
used for civilian honours - 'Commander', 'Officer', 'Order', 'Empire' - bear
distinctly military overtones. And who should become a knight if not a
cavalry officer?
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
What the honours shake-up means for the military
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
British Empire Medal to be abolished.
Non-commissioned officers would receive MBEs
End of the distinction between ranks for military gallantry awards
Military Medal to be abolished.
All ranks eligible for the Military Cross
End to automatic awards, including knighthoods, for top echelons
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
