<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAR 93 / Councils urged to maintain arts cash
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ARTS Council yesterday expressed its concern about cuts in local
authority arts spending.
Local authorities are the main paymasters of the arts in England and Wales,
spending more than Pounds 300m a year, compared with the government's Arts
Council budget of Pounds 225m. But rate-capping and other financial
pressures have persuaded many local authorities to cut their arts budgets
for 1993-94.
Mr Anthony Everitt, secretary-general of the Arts Council, has written to
local authorities urging them to maintain their arts spending.
The Theatre Foundry, a touring arts organisation in Walsall, West Midlands,
has lost its entire local authority revenue of Pounds 75,000 and the nearby
New Vic Theatre in Stoke has had its grant from Staffordshire County Council
cut 40 per cent.
The Northern Ballet has lost Pounds 57,000, reducing its grant to Pounds
200,000, and Watermans Arts Centre in Brentford, west London, has suffered a
15 per cent reduction in grant.
The Arts Council, which received an increase of only 2 per cent in its grant
for 1993-94, can offer no financial help. It is pressing the Department of
National Heritage to make it a statutory requirement for local authorities
to support the arts.
</TEXT>
