<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAR 93 / EC to order BAe repayment: Rover 'sweeteners' and interest
could amount to more than Pounds 60m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE European Commission will next week order British Aerospace to repay
Pounds 44.4m it received in 1988 from the government to 'sweeten' its
purchase of Rover, the car manufacturer.
BAe will also have to repay interest which has accrued since 1990, when the
commission ruled that the sweeteners amounted to illegal state aid. That
ruling was overturned in the European Court of Justice a year ago on a
technicality.
EC officials confirmed yesterday that a recommendation by Mr Karel Van
Miert, the competition commissioner, was on the agenda of next week's
commission meeting and should be approved without further discussion by the
17 commissioners.
Mr Van Miert's proposal does not include a figure for interest charges -
some commissioners had urged that interest be calculated from the date of
the 1988 sale. The charges will be calculated according to UK rules
governing recovery of state aid and some estimates have put the total
repayment at more than Pounds 60m.
The decision should bring to an end 4 1/2 years of court cases and political
wrangling within the commission and between Brussels and BAe.
BAe could launch a further court appeal, however. The company said yesterday
it would not decide whether to challenge the decision until it had been
formally announced. Mr Tony Parry, head of BAe's Brussels office, said
yesterday: 'Clearly we are disappointed that the commission has decided to
apply interest charges in circumstances where we felt that the basis for the
decision was flawed in the first place.'
The commission agreed to BAe's Pounds 150m purchase of Rover in 1988, after
approving a government cash injection into the car group. But the National
Audit Office discovered that the government had also sweetened the sale with
an additional Pounds 44.4m to the aerospace group.
Brussels decided in 1990 that the sweeteners amounted to illegal state aid.
After the ruling was overturned Sir Leon Brittan, then competition
commissioner, pledged a new inquiry. The commission was almost certain to
rule against BAe, because the Court of Justice did not challenge the
substance of the 1990 decision when it overturned the ruling.
Sir Leon's demand in 1990 that the sweeteners should be repaid was seen as a
counterbalance to his decision not to question the Pounds 150m sale price.
He chose not to pursue BAe for repayment of the balance between the price
paid and any higher bid for Rover, in spite of the fact that the National
Audit Office said Pounds 150m was 'substantially' too low.
Sir Leon, a former Conservative cabinet minister, was accused at the time of
being too soft on the government, and last year proposed to omit interest
charges from the repayment.
London stocks, Page 36
</TEXT>
