<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAR 93 / Challenge to news agency
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PRESS Association, the UK's national news agency, appears to be facing
the strongest challenge to its effective monopoly for decades.
Two regional newspaper groups, Northcliffe Newspapers and Westminster Press,
have decided to extend the trial of their own internal service, UK News,
until the end of the this month.
A decision will then be taken on whether to make UK News a permanent
business which will try to recruit further subscribers.
A team of more than 20 journalists at UK News headquarters in Leicester puts
together a daily file of about 15,000 words, making it available to
newspapers ranging from The Gloucester Echo at Cheltenham to the Evening
Advertiser at Swindon.
UK News can call on the work of more than 1,700 journalists from the two
newspaper groups around the country.
Critics of the PA service say that the 100,000 or so words filed each day
are too unwieldly and costly for small regional dailies to handle and that
the fees - ranging from more than Pounds 60,000 a year to over Pounds
200,000 - are too high.
Mr Richard Wooldridge, editorial director of Westminster Press - which, like
the Financial Times, is part of the Pearson Group - said he was pleased with
the UK News's quality and speed of output.
An attempt in 1991 to set up an alternative to PA, which included the
Birmingham Post and Mail, did not succeed.
It is not yet clear whether UK News will be a rival to PA, which is owned by
the regional and local press, or is merely an attempt to change the nature
and cost of the PA service.
Mr Colin Webb, editor-in-chief of PA, would only say last night that the
agency was in 'proper talks' with Westminster Press and Northcliffe
Newspapers.
</TEXT>
