<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAR 93 / Mirror Group trustees object to pension payout
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TRUSTEES FOR the Mirror Group Pension Scheme are objecting to a proposal
that would allow Maxwell company pensioners to start drawing monthly
payments on the Pounds 188m Common Investment Fund which holds the assets of
all four schemes.
The trustees for the four Maxwell schemes have to agree on the basis of
distribution from the fund before any scheme can receive money. The
government's Pounds 2.5m 'drip-feed' to pay pensioners is nearly exhausted
and those in the Maxwell Communication Staff Scheme and the Maxwell
Communication Works Scheme could face cuts in payments after April if a
resolution is not agreed.
Trustees of the four schemes will meet next week to try to reach an
agreement which will allow each scheme to make some withdrawals.
The dispute centres on the method used to calculate the percentage of the
fund allocated to each scheme. Liquidators of Bishopsgate Investment
Management, the fund management company which was controlled by the late
Robert Maxwell and which managed the Common Investment Fund while he was
alive, have been unable to say which assets belong to which scheme.
Bishopsgate failed to keep accurate records of how much each scheme
contributed to the fund, and its records do not accurately record the date
several substantial blocks of assets were transferred out to banks or to
Maxwell's private interests.
The liquidators, Robson Rhodes, have presented the trustees of all the
schemes with 11 different methods of calculating each scheme's share of the
common fund. Several of these show some schemes to owe the common fund
money.
While the trustees of the Maxwell Private Company Scheme, the works scheme
and the staff scheme are said to agree broadly that requiring pension
schemes to pay money into the fund is unrealistic, Mirror Group Pension
Scheme trustees are said to be baulking at some of the proposals.
About 30 MPs have expressed concern that some trustees are carrying out
their duties 'insensitively'.
Sir John Cuckney, chairman of a trust fund which has been collecting
contributions from companies that had dealings with Maxwell companies, has
given no firm assurances to the pension schemes that the Pounds 6m he has
raised so far will be available for monthly pension payments if assets in
the common fund remain off-limits.
</TEXT>
