<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAR 93 / Pit review progress goes underground: The delays to an
eagerly awaited white paper on mine closures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT WAS meant to be short and sharp. When the government buckled under
backbench pressure in October and agreed to review its decision to close 31
coal pits, the widespread assumption was that it was aiming for completion
in January.
When that proved impossible Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry
secretary, said the coal white paper would be published as soon as possible
in February. Now it is unlikely anything will appear before late this month.
After a flurry of activity in the first six weeks of the year the team of
ministers and civil servants leading the coal review has gone quiet. The
heads of the electricity, nuclear and gas industries affected by the review
have heard nothing substantial for weeks.
They are puzzled. After all it is more than three weeks since leaked details
of the draft white paper showed that the government was planning a
relatively simple way out. It rejected the option of reining back nuclear
and gas power, in favour of cutting imports of coal and orimulsion, the
bitumen-based fuel, and persuading electricity generators to buy more
home-produced coal.
The generators' negotiating stance is the main reason for the delay. They
say there is a guaranteed market for only about 40m tonnes of coal over five
years and the government must pay a price if it is to achieve anything near
its 65.5m target.
Ministers are thought to have conceded that extra tonnage must be subsidised
to make it competitive with imports, but arguments remain about what the
subsidy should be, and who should pay the stocking costs for coal surplus to
generators' requirements.
PowerGen, the smaller of the two generators in England and Wales, estimates
stocking costs over five years will be more than Pounds 140m and it wants
the government to pay. The trade department has been considering its
response to Powergen and National Power for more than two weeks.
The delay does not signal that the government has abandoned its draft white
paper plans and is looking for a more radical solution. It is more likely
that the trade department is attempting to square difficult circles
elsewhere before returning to the generators with a compromise.
FIRST it must win acceptance from Brussels for subsidies to keep pits open.
The new competition and energy commissioners are more relaxed about state
aid than their predecessors, but problems remain over any subsidies to coal
after 1995, when the German government plans to reduce its aid to coal.
More difficult still are the trade ministers' problems arising from the
government's slender 20-seat majority in the Commons. The Thatcherite wing
of the Conservative party is uncomfortable about any proposals to prop up
industry with government money, although ministers' preferred solution is
much cheaper than many at first thought - the subsidies and stocking
together are likely to cost less than Pounds 800m over five years.
In delaying full cabinet discussion of the white paper proposals Mr
Heseltine will be able to strengthen his claim for government aid. He will
be able to argue that his department re-examined all the options previously
rejected.
Delaying publication of the white paper could also help deal with potential
dissidents on the left of the party. Even the full 65m tonnes would be
likely to provide a lifeline to fewer than half the threatened pits. Some
Tories have said that is not enough. Some ministers feel their expectations
will fall the longer the review goes on.
In addition, Mr Heseltine may be able to take advantage of this week's
ballots by the National Union of Mineworkers and Nacods pit deputies union
on industrial action, including a one-day strike. If miners vote 'yes' he
can argue that they are out to wreck the industry as in the bad old days. He
can argue that a 'no' means they are past caring.
However close the solution is, it is highly unlikely the white paper will be
published next week.
As the Budget will take up ministers' and parliament's energy and time in
the following week, the week beginning March 22 looks likely. Publication
after April 1 would mean further problems for British Coal - its three-year
contracts with the generators run out on that date and replacements are
unlikely until the white paper is published. Nonetheless, few MPs would be
surprised if publication slipped further.
</TEXT>
