<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAR 93 / Fund managers 'beat markets'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE AVERAGE UK pension fund manager outperformed the domestic equity markets
last year, half of them by one percentage point or more, according to the WM
Company, a pension fund performance measurement service.
The average fund in the WM survey earned 20.8 per cent on UK equities
investments, the best performance for more than a decade.
Meanwhile the FT-A All Share Index rose 20.4 per cent last year. The WM
survey measured the performance of 2,500 pension funds with a combined
market value of Pounds 285bn.
Mr Peter Worrington, marketing director of WM, said that much of the
outperformance comes from UK fund managers underweighting in the shares of
Wellcome Plc, whose share prices are fully reflected in the FT-A Index but
only half of whose shares are actually available in the market.
UK fund managers also earned returns which outstripped stock market indices
in north America, continental Europe and Japan for the first time.
Typically, UK fund managers have underperformed in foreign markets by some
margin.
Of all categories of assets, overseas bonds outperformed all others in 1992,
returning 29.1 per cent over the year. Mr Worrington noted that the shift
into overseas bonds started only 18 months ago and that this category now
accounted for 4 per cent of the assets of the average fund.
Much of the expansion into overseas bonds has occurred at the expense of
domestic bonds and about a quarter of all funds surveyed held no UK bonds.
</TEXT>
