<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAR 93 / Retailer seeks OFT probe of Kellogg prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHOPRITE, the discount food retailer, is calling for an Office of Fair
Trading investigation into Kellogg, the food manufacturer, which threatened
to stop supplying corn flakes to the chain unless it raised the selling
price.
The chain, which is based in the Isle of Man but operates only in Scotland,
has written to the OFT complaining of 'unwarranted interference' by Kellogg,
which told all retailers in January it would stop supplying them if they
sold 500g packs of the cereal below cost price of 96p.
Mr Deryck Nicholson, Shoprite chairman, said his 40 stores had been selling
corn flakes as a loss-leader at 84p for two years, but made a profit on
other Kellogg brands. He said other large retailers, unable to match
Shoprite's price, may have put pressure on the manufacturer.
Mr Nigel Griffiths, Labour's consumer affairs spokesman, tabled a Commons
question this week to Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary,
asking him to investigate the role other large retailers may have played in
Kellogg's decision to stop supplying Shoprite.
Kellogg insisted yesterday that retail pricing on its products was 'for
individual retailers to determine. However, we also believe it is
unreasonable for retailers to use Kellogg's brands as loss-leaders in order
to build their overall business.'
It said its decision to stop supplying retailers who sold Kellogg brands
below cost was in accordance with the 1976 Resale Prices Act. Mr Nicholson
disputed Kellogg's interpretation of the law.
He said special prices for Kellogg's corn flakes and other products had
featured in the launch campaign of many of its stores. 'Kellogg knew this
and supported us with cash incentives that contributed to advertising and
trade promotion. I don't understand why Kellogg is introducing restrictions
now.'
The case is another example of friction between the rapidly expanding
discount retailing sector and big-name suppliers.
Aldi, the German discount food retailer, complained to the OFT that large
retailers were pressing manufacturers into not supplying it when it opened
in the UK in 1990.
The OFT said it could find 'no firm evidence' but would monitor the
situation.
The Monopolies and Mergers Commission is investigating the perfume market at
the request of the OFT, after a complaint from Superdrug, the cosmetics and
toiletries chain, that some leading perfume manu-facturers were refusing to
supply it.
</TEXT>
