<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAR 93 / World Trade News: Foreign companies warned over higher US
taxes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID DODWELL, World Trade Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EUROPEAN companies would be rash to think the US Congress has relented in
its demands for higher taxes on international businesses, Washington tax
lawyers told a meeting of the American Chamber of Commerce in London
yesterday.
The EC will need to lobby in unison if President Bill Clinton's ambitious
deficit reduction package, intended to raise a net Dollars 245bn over the
next five years, is not to include swingeing new transfer pricing rules, the
meeting was told.
Multinational companies operating in the US - the largest group of which are
headquartered in Britain - breathed a deep sigh of relief two weeks ago when
Mr Clinton said in his State of the Union address that new transfer pricing
rules would raise just Dollars 3.8bn over five years. His campaign speeches
last year had hinted that foreign concerns would have to pay an extra
Dollars 40bn in taxes.
However, Mr Greg Jenner, partner in the US law firm McDermott, Will &amp; Emery,
warned that higher taxes could yet be levied. President Clinton might be
forced to find a further Dollars 20bn in revenue to fund programmes demanded
by Congress as a price for approving the administration's deficit reduction
package. 'It is important to keep in mind that the president's proposals
were the first shot,' he said. 'Foreign companies are perceived as easy
targets in the US, and should not think they are out of the woods.'
Demands that foreign companies pay more taxes are based on popular views
that, in order to minimise taxes, many manipulate prices charged on
components passing from parent companies to their US subsidiaries.
Foreign companies complain that these charges are unfounded, and say the new
rules proposed by President Clinton - which call for transfer price analyses
to be carried out at the same time as tax returns are filed - will show
this. In the US, economists worry that higher taxes, and the uncertainty
created by the transfer pricing debate, will discourage new foreign
investment.
Mr Michael Burrell, managing director of the lobbying group Westminster
Strategy, said Mr Clinton's populist appeal meant that lobbying by European
companies 'will have to be framed in terms of the interest of the American
people, and what foreign investment means in terms of US jobs'.
Given the strength of domestic lobbying pressure for foreign companies to
pay higher taxes, he insisted that French, German or British companies would
need to make their case as European companies. 'Europeans have to be seen as
saying the same thing, in the same voice, with co-ordinated action
formulated in coalition.'
Companies needed to target four bodies: the European Commission, EC national
governments, members of the Group of Seven industrial countries, and US
state governments - particularly the home bases of such key US legislators
as Congressman Dan Rostenkowski of Illinois, chairman of the House ways and
means committee, and Senator Daniel Moynihan of New York, chairman of the
Senate finance committee.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
