</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
JAPAN'S governing Liberal Democratic party yesterday yielded to opposition
demands that it consider an income tax cut as a condition for support on the
1993 budget.
The LDP and the three main opposition parties have been at loggerheads for
almost a week over opposition demands for a Y4,260bn (Pounds 25bn) tax cut
to stimulate the flagging economy. LDP leaders last night agreed to study
opposition proposals while drawing up plans for a special package to
stimulate the economy.
The government is coming under mounting pressure from business to take
further measures to provide an economic boost.
