<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAR 93 / Bundesbank ignores appeals and leaves rates unchanged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Bundesbank yesterday ignored foreign and domestic appeals for help to
escape recession and left its important short-term interest rates unchanged.
Despite more gloomy economic news and complaints from Germany's 16 regional
economics ministers, the central bank council decided it was too soon for
more cuts.
The decision not to ease policy surprised some foreign exchange dealers, and
the D-Mark made small gains against European currencies. The French franc
fell below FFr3.40 to the D-Mark at one stage yesterday, closing in London
at FFr3.398.
A month ago the Bundesbank cut the discount and Lombard rates to 8 per cent
and 9 per cent respectively after new turbulence in the European exchange
rate mechanism put the Danish krone under pressure.
In the absence of similar pressures this time the council reverted to its
usual caution. It may have been influenced partly by a government
announcement of an increase in oil and petrol taxes, notionally to fund the
restructuring of the railways.
Inflation, currently 4.2 per cent, remains the bank's principal concern. Its
medium-term aim of bringing the rate of price increases down to 2 per cent,
aided by several modest wage agreements this year, is now being hampered by
government policy.
Import prices, which have fallen steadily in the last few months, are now
2.2 per cent lower than a year ago, the statistics office reported
yesterday.
Germany to lose another 4,500 steel jobs, Page 2
Editorial Comment, Page 15
Currencies, Page 27
World stocks, Page 33
London stocks, Page 36
</TEXT>
