<HEADLINE>
FT  05 MAR 93 / Barclays records Pounds 242m loss and halves dividend: Bank
announces first pre-tax deficit and makes Pounds 2.5bn provision against bad
debts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BARCLAYS BANK, the UK's largest high street bank, yesterday announced its
first pre-tax loss - a deficit of Pounds 242m. It halved its final dividend
and posted the largest provision against bad debts yet allocated by a
British bank.
About Pounds 1.96bn of the Pounds 2.5bn provision was on specific loans in
the UK. Loans to property and construction companies, many made before the
property slump at the end of the 1980s, accounted for 40 per cent of the UK
provisions.
Mr Andrew Buxton, the bank's chairman and chief executive, said his salary
was at least 10 per cent lower than that of Sir John Quinton, his
predecessor. 'The rate for the job has fallen significantly,' he said.
Mr Buxton, who was managing director of the bank under Sir John during the
late 1980s when many lending decisions were made, declined to say when he
would split the two roles as he has promised to do after criticism from
shareholders.
The bank's shares fell by 10.5 per cent to 392p on the day's trading after
the surprise announcement of the cut in the final dividend. Most brokers had
been anticipating lower losses of up to Pounds 100m and the dividend to be
maintained.
Mr Buxton said the 'very disappointing' result and the uncertain outlook for
the coming year meant the bank felt it might not be able to re-build its
ratio of capital to assets sufficiently without cutting the dividend.
He said the bank was changing the way it handles large corporate loans to
ensure that managers who make such loans take individual responsibility. The
careers of some managers involved in poor lending in the past 'had
suffered'.
The decision by Barclays to cut its dividend was only the second time a
British bank has been forced to take such action.
Midland Bank, which was last year acquired by HSBC Holdings, cut its
dividend two years ago.
Barclays was the last of the four traditional high street banks to report
1992 profits. Its loss is one of the biggest incurred by a British clearing
bank, although Lloyds made a loss of Pounds 715m in 1989 because of Third
World debt provisions.
Mr Buxton said the executive directors had recommended a halving of the
final dividend to 6p per share because they were uncertain how far back into
profit the bank would rebound this year.
Of the Pounds 1.96bn provision against possible bad loans in the domestic
bank, Pounds 600m related to 27 single loans of more than Pounds 5m each.
They included a Pounds 240m provision on Barclays' lending to the Imry
property development company.
The bank made its loss despite a substantial increase in its operating
profitability.
Its profit before provisions rose 18 per cent to Pounds 2.4bn, as its UK
business widened margins on loans and increased commission and fees.
The Pounds 98m saved by the dividend cut let Barclays maintain a ratio of
its core capital to assets of 5.5 per cent compared with 5.9 per cent at the
end of 1991.
Some analysts believe the lowest ratio of which the Bank of England is
thought to approve is 5 per cent.
The bank, which disclosed that it cut staff numbers by 6,400 last year and
closed 189 branches, was criticised by unions. The Bifu financial services
union said the loss was from 'monumental incompetence over a long period'.
Editorial Comment, Page 15
Observer, Page 15
Lex, Page 16
