<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 93 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THIS WEEK'S strength in the stock index futures justified itself yesterday,
when the underlying stock market rose sharply ahead of today's policy
meeting at the Bundesbank, writes Terry Byland.
The equity market did not wait for the futures to open but quickly took
advantage of arbitrage opportunities later in the day.
The March contract on the FT-SE 100 Index first traded at 2,912, responding
to the overnight strength of Wall Street. It maintained the premium over
cash at about 12 points, contrasting with the 4-point discount to the fair
value calculation. Trading volume increased substantially in the March
future, which saw 15,637 contracts change hands.
At best, the contract touched 2,934, showing a 12-point premium against the
day's high for the underlying index. This premium was held at the official
close and the future made further progress in late dealings, being quoted at
2,936.
Traded options were also busier, returning total volume of 35,468 lots,
against 32,346. The greatest increase came in the FT-SE option, where
business jumped from 4,986 to 14,726 contracts. The Euro FT-SE was also
active, at 4,292 lots, with Tesco recording 2,108 contracts and Barclays,
where the market is nervous ahead of the results and dividend statement,
1,995 lots. Selling of Guinness shares was reflected in activity in traded
options.
</TEXT>
