<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 93 / International Company News: Overseas earnings help Boral
climb to ADollars 102.8m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRUCE JACQUES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A RISE in overseas earnings helped Boral, the Australian construction and
engineering group, reverse a downward trend in its earnings.
The company raised net profits by 12.7 per cent to ADollars 102.8m
(USDollars 73.4m) in the first half to December, from ADollars 91.3m a year
earlier, on a 10.4 per cent rise in sales to ADollars 2.09bn, from ADollars
1.89bn. The interim dividend is being held at 8 cents a share.
The directors have forecast higher profits for the full year, but said: 'Low
levels of economic activity in Australia continue to constrain demand for
many of Boral's products.
'It is hoped that confidence will improve following the forthcoming federal
election. Non-dwelling building is still at low levels, but government
expenditure on infrastructure should produce a positive contribution in the
next financial year.'
Australian Gas Light, the Sydney-based petroleum utility, has come through a
period of big asset acquisitions and disposals with a strong rise in
first-half earnings.
The company yesterday declared a rise in interim dividend to 7 cents a share
from 6 cents, following a 32.6 per cent advance in earnings to Dollars
A42.4m for the six months to December from Dollars A31.8m. Revenue rose 1.5
per cent to Dollars A477.1m.
Woodside Petroleum, the Australian offshore gas producer, has held its
annual dividend at 8 cents a share, despite dipping into the red in 1992. A
deferred tax provision of ADollars 85.8m against a nil charge previously
sent the company tumbling to net losses of Dollars A22.6m, from profits of
ADollars 116.5m the year before.
