BRIERLEY Investments yes-terday announced a 25 per cent lift in profits in
the half year to NZDollars 112.7m (USDollars 59.6m), largely due to higher
earnings from its New Zealand subsidiaries.
The chairman, Mr Bob Matthew, said the group's biggest investment, the UK
hotel group Mount Charlotte, in which Brierley Investments has a 70 per cent
interest, recorded a modest profit of Pounds 2.1m (USDollars 3m) after a
substantial loss in the previous year.
UK earnings were NZDollars 5m compared with NZDollars 123m last year which
included the subsequently-sold motor division Tozer Kemsley and Millbourn.
Mr Matthew said while the earnings from Mount Charlotte were clearly an
inadequate return on funds employed, the profit turnround came in the face
of a Pounds 8.8m or 3.9 per cent reduction in turnover. He said the result
reflected improving margins, static operating costs and significantly lower
interest charges.
Brierley Investments also had a profit turnround from its Australian
investments, earning NZDollars 23m against a loss of NZDollars 15m in the
comparable period of 1991. However, it incurred a loss of NZDollars 4m in
the US, against a profit of NZDollars 19m in the previous period. Late last
year the company announced its intention to withdraw from the US.
Profits from its New Zealand operations were NZDollars 189m against
NZDollars 190m. Mr Matthew said trading profits in New Zealand at NZDollars
124m were up NZDollars 18m.
