<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAR 93 / International Company News: Mazda and Ford end venture talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   Geneva
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MAZDA and Ford, the Japanese and US motor groups, have abandoned their
negotiations to set up joint vehicle production in Europe.
The breakdown of the talks is a serious setback to Mazda, which is left as
the only one of the top five Japanese carmakers without a production base in
Europe.
Nissan, Toyota and Honda have developed their first European car assembly
plants in the UK, while Mitsubishi is developing a joint car production
venture with Volvo in the Netherlands.
Mazda and Ford, which owns a 25 per cent stake in the Japanese carmaker,
have studied a wide range of possible joint car projects for Europe, but
Mazda said yesterday the talks had been discontinued 'for the time being'.
The fruitless negotiations with Ford of Europe have lasted nearly four years
and followed abortive talks with Saab, the Swedish carmaker.
Mazda said yesterday that 'local sourcing' in Europe remained 'an important
strategic consideration.'
Mazda now planned to intensify its examination of options without Ford of
Europe. 'We will be stepping up our studies of possible co-operative
ventures with other European manufacturers. We would like to resolve the
situation as soon as possible.'
It refused to comment on earlier reports that it had held talks with
Chausson, the French automotive engineering group.
Ford said the talks with Mazda had been terminated because of 'concerns
about the potential profitability of a co-operative European venture. We
could not establish mutually acceptable economic results for a joint
project.'
Mazda's failure to develop a European production base will act as a serious
brake on its growth in Europe during the remainder of the 1990s.
Without local production it will be unable easily to circumvent the quota
restrictions on direct exports from Japan to the European Community, which
are scheduled to last to the end of the decade.
Brussels is already pushing Japan to cut its export shipments to the EC this
year in light of the steep decline forecast in new car demand.
Tokyo and Brussels are in conflict over the interpretation of the
understanding reached in 1991 over the development of Japanese car sales in
Europe during the seven-year transition to a free market in 2000. Tokyo  -
together with the UK government  - insist that local Japanese vehicle
production in Europe is not included under the agreed ceilings for direct
exports and the system for monitoring these shipments.
Mazda is also studying the shipment of cars to Europe from its joint venture
assembly plant with Ford in the US.
</TEXT>
<XX>
